<h2>What Matters vs. What Doesn't</h2>
<p>Color matters less than marketing makes you think. Littmann sells dozens of color combinations and premium finishes — rainbow editions, special editions — at a premium. The acoustics are identical to the standard color versions. Buy the color you like, but don't pay $30–$50 extra for a special finish.</p>
<p>Engraving is worth doing on any stethoscope over $100. A short-term engraving at a local trophy shop or online costs $10–$15. An engraved stethoscope is significantly less likely to be "borrowed" and not returned on a busy unit. Travel nurses especially: engrave your name before your first shift at a new hospital.</p>
<p>Ear tip fit is the most underrated performance variable. Stock ear tips fit poorly for many people. Soft sealing tips ($8–$12 on Amazon) meaningfully improve acoustic performance by improving the seal — often more than upgrading to a more expensive stethoscope would. Change your ear tips before spending $100 more on a new scope.</p>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Travel nurse recommendation:</strong> The Littmann Classic III is the right travel nursing stethoscope — not the Cardiology IV. Travel nurses work in unfamiliar environments with higher risk of equipment going missing. A $120 Classic III does 95% of what the $200 Cardiology IV does, and is $80 cheaper to replace when it disappears on assignment number 3. Save the Cardiology IV for when you're in a permanent ICU position you'll hold for 2+ years.
</div>

